{ and the queen is also only great when it has coordinating pieces }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be2 { [%csl Gg7] } 6... Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Kh1 a5 10. a4 Be6 11. f4 { [%csl Gb6] } 11... Qb6 { [%csl Gb3] } 12. f5 { [%csl Ge6,Gd7,Gb2][%cal Ge6d7,Ge6b3] } 12... Bxb3 $140 13. cxb3 { He has gained space but we have our pawn structure very solid than him } { [%csl Gb4,Gb6] } 13... Qb4 { pressure e4 and an improving move } { [%csl Ge4] } 14. Be3 Nd7 { [%csl Gc4] } 15. Bc4 { [%csl Gg7,Gh6][%cal Gg7c3,Gb2c3,Gb4c3] } 15... Nb6!! { [%csl Ga2] } 16. Na2 { How to evaluvate A Queen for Rook and a bishop } 16... Nxc4!! 17. Nxb4 Nxe3 18. Qe2 Nxf1 { [%csl Gc6] } 19. Nxc6 Ng3+ 20. hxg3 { [%csl Gc6] } 20... bxc6 $17 { Queen is valuable when it has coordinating pieces or targets to attack
here we can evaluvate the position -
1)pawn structure is worse for white
2) it has no targets } 21. b4 axb4 22. a5 c5 23. Ra2 Be5 24. Qc4 Bxg3 25. b3 Rfb8 26. Kg1 Kg7 27. Kf1 Ra7 28. Ke2 Be5 { We should never have unprotected pieces while playing against the queen } 29. Kf3 Bd4 30. g4 g5 31. a6 Be5 32. Ra4 Kf6 33. Kg2 Rh8 34. Qb5 h5 35. gxh5 g4 36. h6 Rxh6 37. Qb8 g3 38. Ra2 Rh2+ 39. Kf3 *


